Here is a complete developer‑focused reference for the Kraken REST and WebSocket APIs. It covers everything from initial setup to placing orders, querying balances, streaming real‑time data, and managing funds, along with a guide to obtaining all tradable assets.

Kraken API – Comprehensive Developer Documentation
Base URL (Spot & Margin): https://api.kraken.com
Version: 0 (all public/private endpoints under /0)
Futures API (separate): https://futures.kraken.com/derivatives (not covered in depth here, but similar auth)

1. Setup Guide
1.1 Creating API Keys
Log in to your Kraken account.

Navigate to Settings → API (or directly to https://www.kraken.com/u/security/api).

Click Generate Key.

Configure permissions:

Query Funds – required for balance, trade balance, ledger queries.

Query Open/Closed Orders & Trades – required for fetching order/trade history.

Modify Orders – required for placing/cancelling orders.

Withdraw Funds – only if you need withdrawal automation.

(Optional) Staking – if you want to stake/unstake assets.

Enter a key description and 2FA if enabled. Click Generate.

Safely store the API Key and Private Key (secret). The secret is shown only once.

1.2 Authentication – Private Endpoint Request Signing
Every private request must include:

API-Key header – your public API key.

API-Sign header – Base64‑encoded HMAC‑SHA512 signature.

nonce parameter – a strictly increasing integer (typically a timestamp in milliseconds).

Signature Construction
Assemble the POST data (URL‑encoded key=value pairs, excluding nonce if it’s already included in the payload; normally you add nonce to the POST data).

Create the string to sign:

nonce + concatenated POST data (the exact form‑encoded string, e.g. nonce=1616492376594&pair=XBTUSD&type=buy&ordertype=market&volume=0.001).

Compute two hashes:

hash = SHA‑256 of the string from step 2.

hmac_key = Base64‑decode of your API secret.

signature = HMAC‑SHA‑512 of (API path + hash) using hmac_key.
Example for endpoint /0/private/Balance:
signature = HMAC-SHA512(hmac_key, "/0/private/Balance" + SHA256(nonce+postdata))

Base64‑encode the signature → API-Sign header.

Python Example – Generating the Signature & Sending a Request
python
import requests, time, hashlib, hmac, base64, urllib.parse

api_key = "YOUR_API_KEY"
api_secret = "YOUR_PRIVATE_KEY"

def kraken_request(endpoint, data):
    url = "https://api.kraken.com" + endpoint
    data["nonce"] = str(int(time.time() * 1000))
    postdata = urllib.parse.urlencode(data)

    # SHA256 of nonce + postdata
    sha = hashlib.sha256(postdata.encode()).digest()

    # Decode API secret
    secret = base64.b64decode(api_secret)

    # HMAC-SHA512 of (path + sha)
    message = endpoint.encode() + sha
    signature = base64.b64encode(hmac.new(secret, message, hashlib.sha512).digest())

    headers = {
        "API-Key": api_key,
        "API-Sign": signature.decode()
    }

    resp = requests.post(url, data=data, headers=headers)
    return resp.json()

# Example: get account balance
print(kraken_request("/0/private/Balance", {}))
Important: The nonce must be larger than any previously used nonce. Using a millisecond timestamp is safe if you don’t submit more than one request per millisecond. For high‑frequency trading, implement a counter that is guaranteed to increase.

