3. WebSocket API
Public WebSocket: wss://ws.kraken.com
Private WebSocket: wss://ws-auth.kraken.com (requires token)

3.1 Public Subscriptions
Subscribe to real‑time streams by sending a JSON message:

json
{
  "event": "subscribe",
  "pair": ["XBT/USD", "ETH/USD"],
  "subscription": {
    "name": "ticker"  // or "ohlc", "trade", "book", "spread", "systemStatus", "heartbeat"
  }
}
book requires a depth parameter (e.g., 10).

OHLC requires interval (minutes).

You can subscribe to multiple pairs in one message.

3.2 Private Feed
Obtain a token via GetWebSocketsToken.

Connect to wss://ws-auth.kraken.com and send:

json
{
  "event": "subscribe",
  "subscription": {
    "name": "openOrders",
    "token": "YOUR_TOKEN"
  }
}
Available private subscriptions:
openOrders, ownTrades, balances.

3.3 Heartbeat & Ping/Pong
The server sends a heartbeat every few seconds. Respond with a pong to keep the connection alive, or set a subscription to heartbeat to monitor.

4. Rate Limits
Kraken employs a dynamic rate‑limiting system.

Public endpoints – less restrictive when no API key is sent; with a key, the counter is based on the key.

Private endpoints – each call has a cost (reflected in the response header X-RateLimit-Refresh).

Typical costs:

Balance – 0.1

AddOrder – 0.1

CancelOrder – 0.1

OpenOrders – 1.0

TradesHistory – 2.0

Ledgers – 2.0

The rate limit window is 15 seconds. If you exceed the limit, you get HTTP 429 and a Retry-After header.

Best practice: throttle requests based on the cost, monitor X-RateLimit-Remaining, and handle 429 gracefully with exponential backoff.

5. Error Handling
All responses contain an error array. A successful call returns "error": []. Common errors:

EAPI:Invalid key – API key wrong or expired.

EAPI:Invalid signature – signature incorrect (check construction).

EGeneral:Invalid arguments – missing or malformed parameters.

EOrder:Insufficient funds – not enough balance.

EAPI:Rate limit exceeded – back off.

EService:Unavailable – internal server error, retry.

EOrder:Order minimum not met – volume below minimum.

Always inspect the error array after every request.

