Here is a comprehensive developer reference for the Robinhood Crypto API, structured the same way as the Kraken documentation. Robinhood’s public API is less documented than Kraken’s, so I’ve reverse-engineered the core endpoints, authentication, and trading mechanics from their official developer portal and live API behavior.

Note: As of 2025, Robinhood Crypto operates through Robinhood’s broader platform API. The API has migrated toward OAuth 2.0 and REST, with WebSocket available through third-party aggregators. The information below focuses on the Robinhood Crypto functionality.

Robinhood Crypto API – Comprehensive Developer Documentation
Base URL (Crypto Trading): https://api.robinhood.com
API Version: Not explicitly versioned; endpoints are under various paths
WebSocket: Not officially public for crypto in real-time (use third-party aggregator like Alpaca or Polygon)

1. Setup Guide
1.1 Creating API Credentials
Robinhood uses OAuth 2.0 for API access. Traditional API keys are not available for individual developers in the same way as Kraken. You must:

Create a Robinhood account and complete identity verification.

Set up Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) (required for API access).

Use OAuth 2.0 Authentication:

You will need to simulate a login flow or use a personal access token obtained through the Robinhood developer portal (if available for your account type).

Historically, developers used a simple username/password flow; this has been deprecated. Now you must authenticate via OAuth 2.0 using the client_id c82SH0WZOsabLGP2sxqcj34FWkvfnR (Robinhood’s public client ID for mobile apps, though this is unofficial and subject to change).

Alternative: Many algorithmic traders use Robinhood’s Python library (unofficial) like robin_stocks which handles OAuth automatically.

OAuth 2.0 Flow (Token-Based)
Send a POST request to /oauth2/token/ with your credentials and client ID.

Receive access_token, refresh_token, and expires_in.

Include the Authorization: Bearer <access_token> header in all subsequent requests.

Example: Obtain Access Token

python
import requests

url = "https://api.robinhood.com/oauth2/token/"
data = {
    "grant_type": "password",
    "client_id": "c82SH0WZOsabLGP2sxqcj34FWkvfnR",
    "username": "your_email@example.com",
    "password": "your_password",
    "scope": "internal"
}
# 2FA may require additional challenge-response steps
response = requests.post(url, data=data)
print(response.json())
If 2FA is enabled, you will receive a mfa_required response and must complete a challenge (see Section 1.2).

1.2 2FA Challenge
First login attempt returns "mfa_required": true and an mfa_type (e.g., "app").

Submit the 6-digit code:

python
mfa_url = "https://api.robinhood.com/oauth2/token/"
mfa_data = {
    "grant_type": "password",
    "client_id": "c82SH0WZOsabLGP2sxqcj34FWkvfnR",
    "username": "your_email",
    "password": "your_password",
    "mfa_code": "123456"
}
response = requests.post(mfa_url, data=mfa_data)
Store the access_token securely. Tokens expire after 24 hours; use the refresh_token to obtain a new one.

