3. WebSocket API
Robinhood does not provide an official public WebSocket stream for crypto price data as of 2025. The WebSocket endpoint that existed (wss://ws.robinhood.com) was discontinued.

Alternatives for Real-Time Data
Polygon.io – Robinhood uses Polygon for market data. You can get a Polygon API key and subscribe to their WebSocket for crypto aggregates.

Alpaca Markets – Provides a free WebSocket for crypto (they are a partner of Robinhood for trading infrastructure).

Polling – Use the REST endpoints with careful rate-limiting (Robinhood allows ~1 request per second per endpoint).

4. Rate Limits
Robinhood does not publish formal rate limits, but empirical testing shows:

REST requests: ~1–2 requests per second per endpoint before you receive 429 Too Many Requests.

Order placement: Maximum ~5–10 orders per minute.

Burst tolerance: You can occasionally send 3–4 requests rapidly, but sustained higher rates will trigger a temporary block.

Mitigation: Implement a 1-second delay between requests, use exponential backoff upon 429s, and cache public data.

5. Error Handling
HTTP status codes used:

200 – Success.

400 – Bad request (invalid parameters).

401 – Unauthorized (token expired or invalid).

404 – Endpoint/resource not found.

429 – Rate limited. Retry after a few seconds.

Common error response format:

json
{
    "detail": "Insufficient funds.",
    "errors": ["Not enough buying power"]
}
Always check status_code and the JSON body for error details before processing.

