8. Best Practices for Algorithmic Trading on Robinhood
Real-time data is a limitation. Since WebSocket is not publicly available for crypto, you must either poll or use a separate data provider (Polygon, Alpaca, Coinbase Pro WebSocket, etc.) for signal generation.

Fractional shares are not the same as fractional crypto. Robinhood allows dollar-based crypto orders (e.g., buy $10 of BTC), which is convenient for dollar-cost averaging algorithms.

OAuth token management is critical. Refresh tokens proactively before expiry to avoid downtime.

No short selling or margin for crypto. Robinhood only supports spot buy/sell of crypto; no derivatives or margin.

Fees are built into the spread. Robinhood advertises "commission-free" crypto, but the spread may be wider than on other exchanges. Always compare your execution price against a reference price.

Rate limiting is more restrictive than Kraken. Design your system to be patient – no more than 1 order per 2–3 seconds to stay under the radar.

Use robin_stocks for prototyping but understand its internals if you move to production.

